I have implemented a browser extension that synchronizes page scrolling progress, which is mainly used for side-by-side comparison of Google Translate translated page and the original page. In the first version, the synchronization standard for scrolling is based on the scroll percentage, which is very intuitive, but because the amount of translated text may be different, the height of each text block will also be different. Following is the current algorithm for scrolling part, I would like to ask you to propose a better approach: maybe DOM based, or maybe something else.

---

const \_onScrollHandler = () => {
 if (scrolling) return

 sendMessage("syncScrollPosition", {
 scrollYPercent: window.scrollY / document.body.scrollHeight
 })
}

const onScrollHandler = throttle(\_onScrollHandler, 50)

onMessage("startSyncForTab", () => {
 window.addEventListener("scroll", onScrollHandler)
})

onMessage("stopSyncForTab", () => {
 window.removeEventListener("scroll", onScrollHandler)
})

const afterApplyScroll = debounce(() => {
 scrolling = false
}, 200)

onMessage("syncScrollPositionForTab", (message) => {
 const { scrollYPercent } = message.data

 scrolling = true

 console.debug("scrolling to", scrollYPercent)

 window.scrollTo({
 top: scrollYPercent \* document.body.scrollHeight,
 behavior: "auto"
 })

 afterApplyScroll()
})<|end_of_turn|>

